Is it possible to regulate systemic risks ?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden shifts in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because, coming out of the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many ways, particularly from the perspective of sovereign debts and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are at the origin of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
In the first place, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove.
Predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed and when no credit is available) will, and probably remains, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Systemic risks are at the origin of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons. In the first place, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove. Predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed and when no credit is available) will, and probably remains, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Systemic instability events impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible.
If this pattern were to repeat, it could erode confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could herald excessive regulations, state intervention, and a disengagement from globalization.
The problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a crisis of sovereign debts of advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can translate into a hazardous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration in tax revenues and an increase in bailout spending.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary counter-cyclical measures.
Undetected systemic risks and imbalances make fiscal policies that appear prudent not actually so.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
