An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative impact on growth that it ultimately self-cancels.
Greece is likely a typical example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can trigger this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, then sovereign states must be vigilant to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and taking swift corrective action.
New detailed legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements, leverage effects, transparency, ratings, and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest, and limits to the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms will soon be implemented.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the likelihood and severity of systemic risks.
But this will not in any way solve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and indicative of instability.
In addition to and as a complement to new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system of surveillance for systemic risks is necessary.
Certain high-ranking politicians and analysts consider such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, to be futile.
Incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex and permanently evolving global financial system make risk detection, according to them, either impossible or so prone to error that this effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we must then accept that we will periodically be in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than the one we thought necessary barely three years ago.
In the domain of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists in rejecting a true proposition, and the other is in accepting a false proposition.
Let's call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
In the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors is likely to have the highest probable cost ?
Opponents of prudent surveillance of systemic risks hold two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable sign of a potentially growing instability.
Searching for such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantaneously.
This position appears to be fallacious.
During the 2008 crisis, for example, some analysts issued warnings, and some investors took note.
However, these warnings may not have been sufficient to be irrefutable, and they certainly did not predict the point of collapse.
They were undoubtedly signs.
The second position is that there are indeed warning signs, but they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This view implies that AQF has a higher probable cost than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or the remedy is worse than the disease.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with the AQF error.
However, RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so the aggregate negative effect of a reaction to false positives (AQF) must be substantial to be convincing.
I am not convinced.
There may be a deeper trend at work.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made in uncertain conditions, and errors are frequent.
The default stance of policymakers in advanced countries appears to be that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless there are good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at the very least debatable.
